Product Measure
---------------

The `product measure`_ is defined as

.. math::

   (خ¼_Aأ—خ¼_B)(Aأ—B)=خ¼_A(A)خ¼_B(B)\\
   A âˆˆ خ£_A\\
   B âˆˆ خ£_B

All combinations of `Aأ—B` do occur.
This is a complete independence of the two variables `A` and `B`.

- If values are exclusive, then they belong to the same variable.
- For a functional dependence only the couples that are elements of the function do occur.  
- A relation we have, if part of the `Aأ—B` space is filled.
  With a probability measure this means that certain `P(aأ—b)=0` and other `P(aأ—b)\neq P(a)P(b)`,
  but rather `P(aأ—b) = P(a|b)P(b) = P(b|a)P(a)`, i.e. the second event's probability
  depends on the first one (`P(a|b)` or `P(b|a)`). If `P(aأ—b)=0`, then `P( a | b ) = P ( b | a ) = 0`:
  `a` does not occur if `b` occurs. But for another `b_1` that might be different,
  i.e. we cannot add the `a` as another value to the `B` variable, but we still can say
  that on `Aأ—B` we have less than maximum information I: 
  `I(Aأ—B) = âˆ« \log P'(aأ—b)dP(aأ—b) \leq âˆ« \log(P'(a)P'(b))P'(a)P'(b)dadb = I(A)+I(B)`
- For complete independence we have the above product space. This might be in a common context,
  but also if the contexts are completely unrelated, e.g. by taking variables from different unrelated times
  and/or from unrelated places, the value couples will fill all of `Aأ—B` and 
  specifically for probability 
  `P(aأ—b) = âˆ« dP(aأ—b) = âˆ« da P'(a)P(b|a) = âˆ« db P'(b)P(a|b) = P(a)P(b)`,
  with `a âٹ‚ A` and `b âٹ‚ B` and `P(b|a) = âˆ«_{\beta âˆˆ b} dP(\beta|a)`.



